{"source_key":"sha256-3b76e7f0fd3ecf2038c9ecb758042f51","record_index":107,"record_hash":"sha256:4f73d812beb8cdd3a9e80bf6b9f6b03e12582c2986316afbb59a7711107b9cc0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:14:40.957Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I read the design doc and the relevant `git-meta-lib` paths. Smallest pragmatic path: add a generic `SyncScope` that only parameterizes refs, state key, and key matching, then reuse the existing serialize/materialize/push machinery with scoped variants.\n\n**Recommended Shape**\n\nAdd a public-ish library type in `git-meta-lib`, probably near [session.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/session.rs:120) or a new `scope.rs`:\n\n```rust\npub struct SyncScope {\n    pub name: String,\n    pub local_ref: String,      // refs/meta/local/agentlog\n    pub remote_ref: String,     // refs/meta/agentlog\n    pub tracking_ref: String,   // refs/meta/remotes/agentlog\n    pub matches_key: fn(&str) -> bool,\n}\n```\n\nFor GitButler, `but-agentlog` owns:\n\n```rust\nfn matches_agentlog_key(key: &str) -> bool {\n    key == \"gitbutler:agent-sessions\" || key.starts_with(\"gitbutler:agent-session:\")\n}\n```\n\nThat keeps GitMeta generic and avoids baking `gitbutler:*` into the library.\n\n**Files To Touch In `git-meta`**\n\n- [db/schema.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/schema.rs:72)\n  Add migration v2 for scoped state. I would not reshape existing `sync_state`; keep compatibility and add:\n\n  ```sql\n  CREATE TABLE sync_scope_state (\n      scope TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n      last_materialized INTEGER\n  );\n  ```\n\n- [db/sync.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sync.rs:143)\n  Keep `get_last_materialized()` / `set_last_materialized()` for default behavior. Add scoped equivalents:\n  `get_last_materialized_for_scope(scope: &str)` and `set_last_materialized_for_scope(scope, timestamp)`.\n\n- [db/sync.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sync.rs:15)\n  Add scoped DB reads, or simpler helper filtering at first:\n  `get_all_metadata_matching(matches_key)`, `get_modified_since_matching(since, matches_key)`, and tombstone variants. The smallest implementation can call the existing full queries and filter in Rust, because agentlog POC scale is acceptable and avoids SQL shape churn.\n\n- [serialize.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/serialize.rs:163)\n  Add `run_scoped(session, scope, now, force_full)`.\n  Reuse `build_tree()` unchanged. The scoped function should:\n  use `scope.local_ref` instead of `session.local_ref()` at line 170;\n  use scoped last-materialized state instead of global line 171;\n  filter metadata/tombstones by `scope.matches_key`;\n  skip global `meta:filter` routing entirely;\n  write exactly `scope.local_ref`, not `destination_ref(\"main\")`;\n  update scoped state only, not global state at line 520-ish.\n\n  I would not try to integrate scoped serialize into the existing routing code on day one. A direct scoped path is clearer and safer.\n\n- [materialize.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/materialize.rs:82)\n  Add `run_scoped(session, scope, now)` that materializes exactly `scope.tracking_ref` into exactly `scope.local_ref`.\n  Reuse `materialize_fast_forward`, `materialize_merge`, and merge helpers, but pass the scoped local ref instead of `session.local_ref()` from line 85.\n\n  Important: even with scoped refs, filter parsed trees to `scope.matches_key` before applying. That is a safety belt against a bad remote ref containing unrelated metadata.\n\n- [pull.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/pull.rs:55)\n  Add `fetch_scoped(session, scope, remote)` or `pull_scoped`.\n  It should fetch:\n\n  ```text\n  refs/meta/agentlog:refs/meta/remotes/agentlog\n  ```\n\n  Then hydrate `meta/remotes/agentlog`.\n\n- [push.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/push.rs:119)\n  Add `push_once_scoped(session, scope, remote, now)` and `resolve_push_conflict_scoped`.\n  Reuse the current flow, but parameterize:\n  `local_ref`, `remote_refspec`, `remote_tracking_ref`, scoped serialize, scoped materialize, and scoped `last_materialized`.\n\n**Ordering I’d Use**\n\nEven though the lifecycle doc says fetch, materialize, serialize, push, I would copy the existing pull safety pattern from [pull.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/pull.rs:106): fetch, hydrate, serialize local scoped state, materialize remote scoped state, serialize merged scoped state, push.\n\nReason: if local agentlog data exists but `refs/meta/local/agentlog` does not yet, materializing first can overwrite list/set/string values in SQLite without a local tree for merge comparison. Agentlog transcripts are list-heavy, so losing local unsynced list entries is the big footgun.\n\n**Materialization Isolation Risks**\n\nThe major isolation risk is not `apply_tree()` by itself. It only applies the maps it receives in [db/sync.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sync.rs:219). The danger is feeding it an unscoped merged tree or using the default local ref.\n\nSpecific risks:\n\n- Current materialize always uses `session.local_ref()` at [materialize.rs:85](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/materialize.rs:85), so a scoped materialize must not call the existing `run()` directly.\n- Current materialize discovers broad refs with `find_remote_refs()` at [materialize.rs:88](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/materialize.rs:88). Scoped materialize should materialize exactly one tracking ref.\n- `apply_legacy_deletes()` at [materialize.rs:228](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/materialize.rs:228) deletes local-tree keys absent from remote. That is safe only if the “local tree” is the scoped local ref. If it accidentally uses `refs/meta/local/main`, remote agentlog absence could tombstone unrelated keys.\n- Global `sync_state.last_materialized` is read by serialize at [serialize.rs:171](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/serialize.rs:171) and push at [push.rs:239](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/push.rs:239). Scoped sync must not advance or consult that global marker.\n\n**GitButler Wiring**\n\nIn `but-agentlog`:\n\n- [Cargo.toml](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/Cargo.toml:15)\n  Point `git-meta-lib` at the local/path or updated rev containing scoped APIs.\n\n- [cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:13)\n  Add `Sync { #[clap(long, default_value = \"origin\")] remote: String }`.\n\n- [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1)\n  Add `sync_agentlog(repo_path, remote)` that creates the `SyncScope` and runs bounded retry:\n  fetch scoped remote if it exists;\n  serialize scoped local;\n  materialize scoped;\n  serialize scoped merged;\n  push scoped;\n  on non-fast-forward, repeat fetch/materialize/serialize/push a small number of times.\n\nRemote missing `refs/meta/agentlog` should be treated as initial publish: serialize local scoped data and push, without materializing an empty state.\n\nNet: add scoped variants by parameterizing the existing implementation, add per-scope materialization state, and keep filtering/ref selection explicit. The biggest thing to resist is “just use filters plus existing push/pull”; that would still couple agentlog sync to global refs and global `last_materialized`, which is where the subtle data-loss bugs live.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:14:40.957Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}